Using OpenStreetMap data in R

Brendan Oâ€™Dowd

2023-01-03

Context

I once had to produce a map examining a land use transition from bogs for peat-cutting to areas for windfarms. I decided it would be useful to import outlines of bogs and locations of wind turbines from OpenStreetMaps.

Setup

We need a couple of packages to start out with. Tidyverse is used for general data manipulation. The sf package is for managing and plotting maps (shapes, more generally) in R. It is installed with tidyverse but not loaded with it. The osmdata package allows us to import OpenStreetMap data into R as either â€˜sfâ€™ or â€˜spâ€™ objects (prefer â€˜sfâ€™ objects). I also need a map of Irish counties. You can get such a map from several places; here I use my own map of 166 local electoral areas and convert that into a county map.

library(tidyverse)
library(sf)
library(osmdata)
library(cowplot)
county_map <- st_read("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/brendanjodowd/maps/main/lea_166.geojson") %>% 
  group_by(COUNTY) %>% 
  summarise(geometry = st_union(geometry) , AREA=sum(AREA))

Importing data from OpenStreetMaps

Query overview

We first create an â€˜Overpass queryâ€™ for OpenStreetMaps using the function opq. This can take as its argument the name of a place, or a bounding box using latitude and longitude coordinates. See the help section on that function for further details.

Then the function add_osm_feature specifies the kinds of map objects that you want to return. It requires both a key and a value argument. The key argument is a feature key, sort of like a category of map object. Some of the options for key are â€˜boundaryâ€™, â€˜amenityâ€™, and â€˜naturalâ€™. The value argument is a specific class of object within that feature key. There is a very wide range of values available within the different keys, such as â€˜forestâ€™, â€˜supermarketâ€™, â€˜cathedralâ€™. Have a look at this list of features for a sense of what can be imported. Iâ€™m not sure if that list is exhaustive, or whether everything on it can be easily imported.

In the example for wind turbines, I use key = "power" and value = "generator". Note that this imports lots of different devices that generate electricity, but I can filter to wind turbines later on.

At the point of the add_osm_feature function, all you have done is defined the query that you want to run, you havenâ€™t actually imported any data yet. That is done by the function osmdata_sf, which gathers the data and outputs an sf object. This function can take a while to run, and may not always run successfully, so it may be best to save the resulting object to file at this point before you make further modifications.

The object returned by osmdata_sf is a list which includes a couple of named dataframes: osm_points, osm_lines, osm_polygons, osm_multilines, and osm_multipolygons. Depending on the objects youâ€™re trying to import, they may be located in one or more of these dataframes. I think it is up to the OpenStreetMaps user who uploads the data in the first place to decide which geometry type is most appropriate.

turbines_query <- opq("Ireland") %>% 
  add_osm_feature(key = "power" , value = "generator") %>% 
  osmdata_sf()

Getting wind turbine locations

Having looked at the various dataframes mentioned above within the turbines_query list-object, I found that all of the wind turbines are in the osm_points dataframe. Here I create a copy of that osm_points dataframe called turbines. One of the columns is called generator.method, and I filter just the rows where that is equal to "wind_turbine". There are a lot of other variables, so I choose just a few that are of interest to me using select. Note that the GEOMETRY column is kept by default and doesnâ€™t have to be specified in select for sf objects.

turbines <- turbines_query$osm_points

turbines <- turbines %>% 
  filter(generator.method=="wind_turbine") %>% 
  select(name, generator.output.electricity, manufacturer, operator)

Bogs

There isnâ€™t a specific key/value feature for â€˜bogsâ€™ as we might understand them in Ireland, but I found that the "wetland" feature matched my requirements for this project.

bogs_query <- opq("Ireland") %>% 
  add_osm_feature(key = "natural" , value = "wetland") %>% 
  osmdata_sf()

It turns out that some bogs/wetlands are uploaded as polygons and others are uploaded as multipolygons, and so they are contained within two different dataframes within the bogs_query list-object. I decide to combine them both using bind_rows to create a new dataframe called bogs. Then I select a few variables which are of interest.

bogs <- bind_rows(bogs_query$osm_polygons  ,
                 bogs_query$osm_multipolygons) %>% 
  select( name , wetland)

Some extra turbines.

Thereâ€™s actually a new windfarm in a part of Tipperary that I wanted to include. I found these coordinates manually from Google Maps, and they can be turned into an sf object as shown below. Their coordinate reference system (CRS) is set to be the same as that for county_map (WGS 84).

new_turbines <- tribble(
  ~lat , ~long,
  52.61594839110318, -7.69242746150073,
  52.61276941295214, -7.686762636061125,
  52.60836536508515, -7.682256524916086,
  52.636185727368925, -7.660562886949663,
  52.64386809365363, -7.651893987413578,
  52.64449732500331, -7.66927492954084,
  52.65019471092566, -7.659118918231185,
  52.65509578182991, -7.661757585929191,
  52.65509578182991, -7.64464259368543,
  52.65822504258744, -7.651925569108475,
  52.664671978288375, -7.655918392931982,
  52.665973321164486, -7.641241345202222,
  52.671348708560096, -7.649956877758161,
  52.67446892090545, -7.657981275577273
  ) %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("long", "lat"), crs = st_crs(county_map))

Plotting

Ok, letâ€™s map all of this for a section of Tipperary. Iâ€™m cropping to this part of the country using xlim and ylim. Turbines are plotted as open circles using shape=1 (there are a couple of places online where you can check out all the different point shapes available, here is one website that has them). Axes and other unwanted plot items are removed using theme_void. The background is set to a dark grey colour using the plot.background argument within a theme function.

ggplot(county_map)+
  geom_sf(size=1.5, fill=NA , colour = "white") +
  geom_sf(data=bogs, fill="#58764C", colour="#58764C", size=1) +
  geom_sf(data=turbines, colour = "#00A2FF", shape=1, size=2 ) + 
  geom_sf(data=new_turbines, colour = "#FB37B4" , shape=1, size=2 ) + 
  xlim(-8.4,-7.3) + ylim(52.5, 53.1) + 
  theme_void() + 
  theme(plot.background = element_rect(fill = "#2B2727"))
